Reasoning¶

Now, we are going to study the 3D version of the Hindmarsh-Rose neuronal model, e.g., the one which is composed of three differential equations:

$$ \begin{gather*} \dot x = y - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - z \\ \dot y = C - Dx^2 - y \\ \dot z = r(s(x-x_1)-z) \\ \\ \text{Once more, here where $I$ will follow the next dynamic:} \\ I = \begin{cases} I(\infty), & \text{if there is not a pulse} \\ I_0, & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \\ \end{gather*} $$

The complete Hindmarsh-Rose neuron mathematical model implementation can be found in the /lib/hindmarsh_rose.py file, where it has been fully parameterized to support multiple scenarios.

Once more, to avoid long stabilization times of our system we will assign the following initial values by default: $$ \begin{gather*} x_0 = -0.8610800560651974, & y_0 = -2.7984503338411115, & z_0 = 0 \end{gather*} $$

THEORY ABOUT THE 3D HR MODEL¶

Critical points¶

Now, we are going to study the 3D version of the Hindmarsh-Rose neuronal model, e.g., the one which is composed of three differential equations:

$$ \begin{gather*} \dot x = y - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - z \\ \dot y = C - Dx^2 - y \\ \dot z = r(s(x-x_1)-z) \end{gather*} $$

First we equals to zero:

\begin{gather*} \dot x = y - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - z = 0\\ \dot y = C - Dx^2 - y = 0 \\ \dot z = r(s(x-x_1)-z) = 0 \end{gather*}

In summary: $$ \begin{gather*} y - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - z = 0\\ y = C - Dx^2 \\ s(x-x_1)-z= 0 \rightarrow z = s(x-x_1) \end{gather*} $$

We substitute in the previous system, to get x:

$$ (C - Dx^2) - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - S(x-x_1) = 0 \\ C - Dx^2 - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - S(x-x_1) = 0 \\ -Ax^3 + (B-D)x^2 + C + I -S(x-x_1) = 0 \\ -Ax^3 + (B-D)x^2 + C + I -Sx + Sx_1 = 0 \\ -Ax^3 + (B-D)x^2 -Sx +(I + C + Sx_1) = 0 $$

We know that:

$$ I = 0, A = 1, B = 3, C = 1, D= 5, \mu = r = 0.005, S = 4, x_1= -1.6 $$

Then we have:

$$ -Ax^3 + (B-D)x^2 -Sx +(I + C + Sx_1) = 0 \\ -x^3 +(3 - 5)x^2 -4x + (0 + 1 + (4*(-1.6))) \\ -x^3 -2x^2 -4x + (1 - 6.4) \\ -x^3 -2x^2 -4x - 5.4 = 0 $$

We resolve:

Critical points stability¶

Here we are going to study the nulclines viusally and obtaining their critical points eigenvalues.

Before working on these points we should compute the Jacobian of our dynamical system:

$$ \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial y} & \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial z}\\ \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial y} & \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial z}\\ \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial y} & \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial z} \end{pmatrix} $$

We go row for row, first for $\dot x$

$$ \begin{gather*} \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial x} = 3Ax^2 - 2Bx \\ \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial y} = 1 \\ \frac{\partial \dot x}{\partial z} = -1 \end{gather*} $$

Second, for $\dot y$ $$ \begin{gather*} \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial x} = -2Dx\\ \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial y} = -1 \\ \frac{\partial \dot y}{\partial z} = 0 \end{gather*} $$

Last, for $\dot z$

$$ \begin{gather*} \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial x} = rS\\ \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial y} = 0\\ \frac{\partial \dot z}{\partial z} = -r \end{gather*} $$

We end at:

$$ \begin{pmatrix} -3x^2 + 2Bx & 1 & -1\\ -2Dx & -1 & 0\\ rS & 0 & -r \end{pmatrix} $$

We know that: $$ I = 0, A = 1, B = 3, C = 1, D= 5, \mu = r = 0.005, S = 4, x_1= -1.6 $$

So: $$ \begin{pmatrix} -3x^2 + 6x & 1 & -1\\ -10x & -1 & 0\\ 0.02 & 0 & -0.005 \end{pmatrix} $$

We can see that our critical point is:

  • Stable in the OX (real & negative).
  • Stable in OY (real & negative).
  • Stable in OZ (real & negative).

So, it could be a stable equilibrium!

OX - Nulcline¶

If we have $\dot x = 0$, then: $$ \begin{gather*} y - Ax^3 + Bx^2 + I - z &=& 0 \\ y &=& Ax^3 - Bx^2 - I + s(x - x_1) \end{gather*} $$

In [ ]:
def dx_nul(
        a: float, x: np.array, b: float, i: float,
        x_1: float, s: float, **kwargs):
    '''
    This method will obtain the dx/dt nulcline.

    :param a: A parameter.
    :param x: OX linespace.
    :param b: B parameter.
    :param i: I_inf/I_0 parameter
    :param x_1: X_1 parameter.
    :param s: S parameter.
    :return np.array: A series of float
    values with the dx/dt nulcline
    '''
    return a*(x*x*x) - b*(x*x) - i + s*(x - x_1)

OY - Nulcline¶

If we have $\dot y = 0$, then: $$ \begin{gather*} C - Dx^2 - y &=& 0 \\ y &=& C - Dx^2 \end{gather*} $$

def dy_nul(c: float, d: float, x: np.array, **kwargs):
    '''
    This method will obtain the dy/dt nulcline.

    :param c: C parameter.
    :param d: D parameter.
    :param x: OX linespace.
    :return np.array: A series of float
    values with the dy/dt nulcline
    '''
    return c - d*(x*x)

OZ - Nulcline¶

If we have $\dot z = 0$, then: $$ \begin{gather*} z &=& sx - sx_1 \end{gather*} $$

In [ ]:
def dz_nul(x: np.array, x_1: float, s: float, **kwargs):
    '''
    dz/dt integration.

    :param x: OX linespace.
    :param x_1: X_1 parameter.
    :param s: S parameter.
    :return float: The system's integration.
    '''
    return s*x - s*x_1

HR-3D system & pulse dynamic (I)¶

Here we are going to implement a function to generate a values series for the presynaptic current.

It's going to build it according to the type of experiment that we want to recreate with the neuron.

In [ ]:
def generate_i_sequence(length: int, case_type=0, i_inf=0, i_sup=1):
    
    zeros = np.ones(length, dtype=int) * i_inf  # I_CASE.no_current

    if case_type == I_CASE['one_pulse_10ms']:
        zeros[30*FRAME_RATE:40*FRAME_RATE] = i_sup
    elif case_type == I_CASE['one_pulse_3ms']:
        zeros[46*FRAME_RATE:49*FRAME_RATE] = i_sup
    elif case_type == I_CASE['one_pulse_3ms_10ms']:
        zeros[46*FRAME_RATE:49*FRAME_RATE] = i_sup
        zeros[89*FRAME_RATE:109*FRAME_RATE] = i_sup
    elif case_type == I_CASE['sustained_on']:
        zeros = np.ones(length, dtype=int) * i_sup

    pulse_sequence = deque(list(zeros))
    return pulse_sequence

The generate_series function generates time series for these variables:

  • x: The membrane potential.
  • y: The recovery variable, which in this case reflects the activity of potassium channels.
  • z: The inward slow current, also known as the adaptation current.
  • first_spikes: It contains the first spikes of the neuron bursts.
  • hyperpol_points: It contains the points of maximum hyperpolarization.
In [ ]:
def generate_series(neuron: HindmarshRoseNeuron, pulse_sequence: None, repetitions=1, value_drops=0):

    x_array = []
    y_array = []
    z_array = []

    first_spikes = []
    hyperpol_points = []

    t_actual = 0

    is_there_first_spike = False

    drops = value_drops

    sequence_length = len(pulse_sequence)

    for t in tqdm(range(sequence_length * repetitions)):

        if pulse_sequence is None or len(pulse_sequence) == 0:
            e_i = 0
        else:
            e_i = pulse_sequence.popleft()
            pulse_sequence.append(e_i) # Con esto conseguimos que la cola doblemente terminada acte como una cola circular

        new_state, spike, hiperpol = neuron.signal_step(e_i=e_i)

        t_actual += 1
        drops += 1

        if drops >= value_drops:
            x_array.append([t_actual, new_state[0]])
            y_array.append([t_actual, new_state[1]])
            z_array.append([t_actual, new_state[2]])
            drops = 0

        # Si ya hemos registrado el primer pico de la serie esperamos a bajar del umbral de activacin para resetear el flag
        if new_state[0] < neuron.umbral_subida_:
            is_there_first_spike = False

        # Compruebo si se trata del primer spike
        if spike and not is_there_first_spike:
            first_spikes.append([t_actual, new_state[0]])
            is_there_first_spike = True

        # Compruebo si hay inicio de hiperpolarizacin
        if hiperpol:
            hyperpol_points.append([t_actual, new_state[0]])

    return x_array, y_array, z_array, first_spikes, hyperpol_points

We note that, unlike the 2D model in which the dynamics remained oscillatory generating spikes at a fixed frequency, here the frequency decreases until we leave the oscillatory cycle.

This may be due to the inclusion of the z component which, as we have seen in the Hindmarsh and Rose paper, models an output current with a slower velocity compared to the other two variables.

Bursting activity¶

The 3D model introduces two new modes of operation in the neuron thanks to the addition of the third time-varying variable z. This allows the neuron to transition between two different dynamics when the current reaches a certain value (in our case I=2). This allows the neuron to transition between two different dynamics when the current reaches a certain value (in our case I=2), we are going to set the value of mu parameter to have a better view of the plot.

NOTE

Please remember that $\mu = r$ in our differential system.

Finally, we think that it would be valuable to comment that, the previous 3D plots, show how our system enters into a Supercritical-Hopf Bifurcation switching between a limit cycle that ends into a stable mechanich which returns to the limit cycle in an infinite loop.

This mechanic explains how the bursting activity emerges where, the spiking peaks in the bursting mode, are explained by the limit cycle part while the silent periods between bursts is explained by the stable mechanich until it returns to the beginning of the limit cycle mechanic (burst-silence-burst-silence, ...)
